{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Gcyuns91dNtznGb5VZxx4f","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture:\n\n1. The StatefulSet mounts the `es-file-realm-aggregate` secret as the file realm (`users`, `users_roles`, `roles.yml` files)\n2. The precondition created:\n   - `es-file-realm-aggregate` secret with only `ops-user`\n   - `user-provided-file-realm` secret with only `report-user`\n3. The oracle checks that:\n   - `es-file-realm-aggregate` contains BOTH `ops-user` AND `report-user` in `users` and `users_roles`\n4. Each user has specific permissions: `ops-user` queries cluster health while `report-user` queries index counts\n\nThe strategy is to merge the two secrets by extracting both sets of credentials, combining the `users` and `users_roles` files, and updating `es-file-realm-aggregate` with the merged content. Since Elasticsearch automatically reloads the file realm when the mounted secret changes, the new credentials should take effect after a brief delay.\n\nBut I need to verify that Elasticsearch is actually configured to use file realm authentication and is reading from the correct mounted path—let me check the elasticsearch.yml configuration in the configmap to confirm the setup.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4463,"cache_read_input_tokens":38448,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4463},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fdc5865e-b097-464b-9957-7edb5f96d728","uuid":"8d092dbf-1ae5-4768-bc51-c6a24b9fe636","request_id":"req_011CcfqDxw2q1AnPZdYJhabi"}
